      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Debugging a memory leak in a resource-constrained environment can be challenging, but we can employ some strategies to help you track it down. \n\nFirst, let's analyze the code. The `process_sensor_data` function is the culprit, and it's allocating memory on the heap. The issue is that the buffer is not being freed, so it's accumulating memory over time. \n\nTo debug this, we can use a combination of techniques. Since we can't use Valgrind, we'll rely on manual inspection and profiling. \n\n1. **Add logging**: We can add logging statements to track when the buffer is allocated and when it's sent to the telemetry module. This will help us identify when the buffer is being used and when it's not.\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet == nullptr) return;\n\n    // Allocate buffer for processing\n    uint8_t* processing_buffer = new uint8_t[packet->size];\n    \n    // Log allocation\n    log(\"Allocated buffer of size %d\", packet->size);\n\n    // Copy data\n    std::memcpy(processing_buffer, packet->data, packet->size);\n\n    // Perform complex DSP operations",
