      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Logging can be a challenge when dealing with high-frequency events. Instrumenting the heap itself can be a good approach to track memory usage. \n\nOne technique is to use a custom memory allocator that provides additional information about heap allocations. We can create a custom allocator that keeps track of the total heap usage and provides a way to detect when memory is freed.\n\nAnother approach is to use a simple heap tracking mechanism, such as a \"heap counter\" that increments every time memory is allocated and decrements when it's freed. This can give us a rough estimate of the total heap usage.\n\nHowever, to catch the exact moment a pointer goes out of scope, we can use a combination of the heap counter and a \"memory fence\" mechanism. We can use a memory fence to ensure that all memory allocations are visible to the heap counter, and then use a separate mechanism to detect when a pointer goes out of scope.\n\nOne way to implement this is to use a \"memory fence\" register that can be set to trigger an interrupt when a memory allocation is made or when a pointer goes out of scope. This can give us a precise timestamp for when the memory is freed.\n\nHere's an example of how we can implement a simple heap counter using a memory fence",
